Key takeaways.

Primitive types are fixed-size values that map directly to bytes in memory. Their size determines their range, their speed, and their memory footprint.

For integers, use int as the default. Switch to long when values can exceed about two billion. Be aware that in Kotlin, integer overflow wraps silently — Python is immune.

For decimal numbers, use double for general arithmetic. Never use float or double for money or anything requiring exact decimal results — use Decimal in Python or Big Decimal in Kotlin.

Characters are just numbers. The A-S-C-I-I tricks — letter minus A for an alphabetic index, digit minus zero for a numeric value — appear constantly in string and array problems.

Python is dynamic and wraps everything in heap objects. Kotlin is static and uses true stack-allocated primitives for local variables, with boxing when primitives go into collections. And type conversion is always explicit — both languages require you to be clear about what you want, which prevents silent precision loss.
